This paper deals with natural language processing and machine learning techniques for predicting discourse connectives, which are important for building coherent and fluent discourses. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also uses a recently proposed decomposable attention (DA) model, which falls under the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The evaluation of the model's performance involves F1 scores, which are commonly used in machine learning and fall under the sub-category of cs.LG (Learning). The paper also mentions the use of documents retrieved from the Web, which suggests a possible connection to information retrieval (cs.IR) and neural networks (cs.NE).
